value.value: any structural anomaly of the clusters of neurons in the somatic peripheral nervous system which contain the cell bodies of sensory nerve axons, interneurons and non-neuronal supporting cells
any structural anomaly of a group of sensory nerve cell bodies located on the dorsal spinal roots within the vertebral column
loss of segmentation pattern of dorsal root ganglia or loss of regular spacing between the ganglia
loss of DRG spacing pattern and the appearance of two or more ganglia as one
reduced size a group of sensory nerve cell bodies located on the dorsal spinal roots within the vertebral column
any structural anomaly of cells that innervate an effector (muscle or glandular) tissue and are responsible for transmission of sensory impulses
fewer than normal numbers of cells that innervate an effector (muscle or glandular) tissue and are responsible for transmission of sensory impulses
any changes in the placement, morphology or number of sensory nerve fibers to sensory termini or to spinal cord
any structural anomaly of any of the peripheral receptors for pain, including receptors sensitive to painful mechanical stimuli, extreme heat or cold, and chemical stimuli
anomaly in a sensory receptor that may be stimulated by mechanical, thermal or chemical means
any structural anomaly of any of the cellular receptors that mediate the sense of temperature; in vertebrates, these are most often located under the skin
anomaly in the receptors of the body, usually nerve termini, that respond to mechanical pressure or distortion
any structural anomaly of the neuronal receptors that respond to mechanical pressure or distortion in the skin
anomaly of the subcutaneous mechanoreceptors that innervate hair follicles of guard hairs, and are involved in the amplification of slow-moving and/or light touch stimuli signals
absence of the subcutaneous mechanoreceptors that innervate hair follicles of guard hairs, and are involved in the amplification of slow-moving and/or light touch stimuli signals
more robust innervation of the subcutaneous mechanoreceptors that innervate hair follicles of guard hairs, and are involved in the amplification of slow-moving and/or light touch stimuli signals
anomaly of the subcutaneous mechanoreceptors that innervate tylotrich hair follicles
more robust innervation of the hair tylotrich cells

anomaly of the subcutaneous mechanosensitive D-hair (down-hair) neurons, which innervate hair follicles, and are characterized by a large-amplitude Cav3.2 T-current involved in the amplification of slow-moving and/or light touch stimuli

absence of the subcutaneous mechanosensitive D-hair (down-hair) neurons, which innervate hair follicles, and are characterized by a large-amplitude Cav3.2 T-current involved in the amplification of slow-moving and/or light touch stimuli

more robust innervation of the subcutaneous mechanosensitive D-hair (down-hair) neurons, which innervate hair follicles, and are characterized by a large-amplitude Cav3.2 T-current involved in the amplification of slow-moving and/or light touch stimuli
any structural anomaly of any of the numerous oval bodies found in the dermal papillae of glabrous skin that transmit information about skin motion and slipping objects
larger than average size of any of the numerous oval bodies found in the dermal papillae of glabrous skin that transmit information about skin motion and slipping objects

more robust supply of nerve fibers connected to any part of any of the numerous oval bodies found in the dermal papillae of glabrous skin that transmit information about skin motion and slipping objects
any structural anomaly of the modified epidermal cells located in the stratum basale and found mostly in areas where sensory perception is acute
greater than the normal number of the modified epidermal cells located in the stratum basale and found mostly in areas where sensory perception is acute
more robust supply of nerve fibers connected to the modified epidermal cells located in the stratum basale and found mostly in areas where sensory perception is acute

any structural anomaly of any of the rapidly adapting mechanoreceptors found in subcutaneous tissue beneath both hairy and glabrous skin, and which normally contain an afferent nerve fiber surrounded by a capsule with multiple concentric layers; trasmit signals generated by vibrations when grasping an object

any structural anomaly in the sensory cells in the subcutaneous tissue of the digits specialized to transduce mechanical stimuli, skin stretch, direction of object motion, hand shape and finger position
any structural anomaly of the receptors that respond to mechanical pressure or distortion in the skeletal muscle
any structural anomaly of the sensory organ in muscle; involved in the stretch reflex and sensitive to stretch velocity
missing sensory organ in muscle; involved in the stretch reflex and is sensitive to stretch velocity

label.value: partial loss of primary muscle spindle

value.value: missing a portion of the sensory organ in muscle; involved in the stretch reflex and is sensitive to stretch velocity
any structural anomaly of the sensory organ in muscle; involved in the stretch reflex and not sensitive to stretch velocity
lack of the sensory organ in muscle; involved in the stretch reflex and is not sensitive to stretch velocity

label.value: partial loss of secondary muscle spindle

value.value: missing a portion of the sensory organ in muscle; involved in the stretch reflex and is not sensitive to stretch velocity
any structural anomaly of the sac or its contents that encloses the articulating ends of bones participating in a synovial joint
missing sac that encloses the articulating ends of bones participating in a synovial joint
any structural anomaly of the sensory organ in muscle that is involved in regulating muscle tension
missing sensory organ in muscle that is involved in regulating muscle tension
any structural anomaly of any of the cells specialized to detect chemical substances and relay that information centrally in the nervous system
any structural anomaly of the small sensory organs located in the tongue that contain gustatory receptor cells, basal cells, and supporting cells

any structural anomaly of the proteins, usually projecting from the cilia of olfactory receptor neurons, that specifically bind odorant molecules and trigger responses in the specialized neurons of the olfactory epithelium
any structural anomaly of a cell specialized to detect and transduce light, including rods and cones of the retina

any structural anomaly of one of the photoreceptor cell types of the vertebrate retina, in which the photopigment is in stacks of membranous disks separate from the outer cell membrane; rods are more sensitive to light than cones, but rod mediated vision has less spatial and temporal resolution than cone vision

any structural anomaly of one of the photoreceptor cell types in the retina, in which the photopigment is in invaginations of the cell membrane of the outer segment; cones are less sensitive to light than rods, but they provide vision with higher spatial and temporal acuity, and the combination of signals from cones with different pigments allows color vision
any structural anomaly of the part of the autonomic nervous system that innervates smooth muscle, cardiac muscle and glands and mediates the body's response to stressful situations

any structural anomaly of the ganglia of the sympathetic nervous system including the paravertebral and the prevertebral ganglia, which include the sympathetic chain ganglia, the superior, middle, and inferior cervical ganglia, and the aorticorenal, celiac, and stellate ganglia

overdevelopment or increased size, usually due to increased cell number, of the groups of postsynaptic neurons located at intervals along the sympathetic trunk, including the superior cervical, middle cervical and stellate (cervicothoracic) ganglia as well as the thoracic, lumbar and sacral ganglia

overdevelopment or increased size, usually due to increased cell number, of the sympathetic ganglia located in front of the vertebral column and are associated with the major branches of the abdominal aorta; these include the celiac, aorticorenal, superior and inferior mesenteric ganglia
